                    <title>Hi, Tim,
This isn&#039;t an uncomm…</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Comment:10442"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2012-06-25:6456126:Comment:10442</id>
                                        <updated>2012-06-25T15:50:34.700Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>corey haines</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/128952ghvkcvj</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;Hi, Tim,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This isn&#039;t an uncommon response. There are two things I think cause this. Although I don&#039;t know if these are your reasons, they definitely are ones that can come up. Perhaps some other experience facilitators can chime in, as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Having too few sessions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3 sessions isn&#039;t enough, especially if this is the first time. The day of coderetreat builds itself up over the 5-6 sessions. Each session builds upon the previous sessions, so that, by the end of the day,…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;Hi, Tim,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This isn&#039;t an uncommon response. There are two things I think cause this. Although I don&#039;t know if these are your reasons, they definitely are ones that can come up. Perhaps some other experience facilitators can chime in, as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Having too few sessions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3 sessions isn&#039;t enough, especially if this is the first time. The day of coderetreat builds itself up over the 5-6 sessions. Each session builds upon the previous sessions, so that, by the end of the day, the &#039;frustration&#039; people feel doesn&#039;t take on a negative bent, but rather a desire to continue thinking about it. This is one of the reasons that I&#039;m not a support of &quot;mini-coderetreat&quot; as a large group activity, especially for people who are experiencing it for the first time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Not introducing different constraints for each session.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What sort of variation did you provide for each session? As developers, we have spent our careers focused on &#039;getting things done&#039; and &#039;going faster,&#039; so it is difficult to break out of this mentality. By introducing different constraints, each session takes on a different feel. Over the course of the day, the problem is approached in a different manner. This creates something that can be focused on during each session.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is tough for people to just focus on an abstract idea of &quot;the code and its beauty.&quot; &lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
                                    </entry>
